			<ns0:name>j...@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/109636895838879576326/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">PNaCl could support FP16 in two ways:
 - Allow conversions to/from FP16 and FP32/FP64.
 - Allow FP16 math.

The former seems easier to support even if an architecture has no built-in support for conversions. This might already be built into LLVM.

The later probably requires emulation (or fast-math conversion) on architectures that don't support it.

FP16 is used in a few specific cases, and if supporting it is easy enough then we should because it plays to PNaCl's strengths.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2013-04-10T23:34:26.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2013-04-10T23:28:50.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>Assigned</ns2:status><ns2:owner>
